255":"about 1255","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","England":"England","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England":"Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Daubeny","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Daubney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Daubney","meanings":["English (mainly Lincolnshire; of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from any of several places in northern France called Aubigny, named with the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Albinius</i> (a derivative of Latin <i>albus</i> ‘white’; compare   Albin  ) + the habitational suffix <i>-acum</i>. Compare   Dabney  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Oliver","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French name, <i>Olivier</i>, recorded as the name of one of Charlemagne's paladins (retainers), the close companion in arms of Roland in the Chanson de Roland. Whereas Roland is headstrong and rash, Oliver is thoughtful and cautious. Ostensibly this name derives from Late Latin <i>olivarius</i> ‘olive tree’ (  compare  Olive  ), but Charlemagne's other paladins all bear solidly Germanic names, so it is more probably an altered form of a Germanic name, perhaps distantly connected with Old Norse <i>Óleifr</i> ‘ancestral relic’. It has remained in more or less continuous use since the medieval period, becoming ever more popular since the 1980s."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":34,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Oliver Daubeny of d'Aubigny was born about 1225, in England as the son of N. N. Daubeny and N. N.. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mabel Tywe. He died before 5 April 1271."},"et":{"about 1225–before 5 April 1271":"umbes 1225–enne 5. aprilli 1271","1225–1271":"1225–1271","1230–1271":"1230–1271","1255–1271":"1255–1271","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1259":"1259","about 1270":"umbes 1270","1225":"1225","1255":"1255","before 5 April 1271":"enne 5. aprilli 1271","about 1225":"umbes 1225","1230":"1230","about 1255":"umbes 1255","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","England":"England","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England":"Watton at Stone, Hertfordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1225–before 5 April 1271":"noin 1225–ennen